{"text": "is a time management game and is the sequel to  .  This will be a bit of a spoiler for those who are not aware of how   ended, so some forewarning there.  ;)  At the end of  , Ragnar, king of the Vikings, defeated Gesta, the witch who had kidnapped his three daughters: Summer, Autumn, and Winter.  In  , Gesta returns and this time, she reveals why she had kidnapped Ragnar's daughters in the first place.  It turns out that there's an even greater evil out there than Gesta.  Along with repairing his kingdom, Ragnar must confront this evil and defeat it, along with help from his daughters.  That's the basic gist of the story. As for the gameplay, it retains a lot from the first  .  You have buildings that can help produce resources: food, wood, and gold.  There are a total of 45 story levels and 5 bonus levels.  Each level has a number of tasks to complete and you can earn anywhere from 1 to 3 stars, depending on how quickly you complete all tasks.  You can choose among relaxed (no timed), normal, or multiclick (you can queue multiple tasks at once) modes.  I chose multiclick mode, as I like to queue tasks and plan ahead.  Although there are no Steam achievements, there are plenty of in-game achievements, a few which are secret achievements.  The newest addition, gameplay wise, is the daughters tent.  The daughters tent is needed because in later levels, evil roots will start to block workers' path and surround buildings, preventing resources from being produced.  The daughters can help get rid of these roots (provided that there is enough food and gold).   Now that I've gone over the story and gameplay, I'll move onto my review.  It's been a while since I last touched a   game but I can say that   is way more challenging than the first one.  (This is assuming that you choose to play in timed mode.)  The later levels especially prove to be quite daunting to complete and they require both the right timing and correct use of bonus to earn 3 stars.  It can get frustrating if you're a novice of TMs but quite doable for those who are experts.  There is more story as well, as there are more cutscenes and such.  The art is in the same beautiful style as the previous game and the music is the same, too.   Overall, I enjoyed   although I slightly liked the first   more.  Would I recommend it at the current asking price?  Well, if you're going for full completion (getting 3 stars on all levels and earning all in-game achievements), then yes, it is.  You'll get plenty of gameplay for your money's worth.  However, if you simply want to play through the game just for the sake of the story, then it's better to wait for a sale, when it can be quite the bargain.  ^^", "appid": "573340", "steamid": "profiles/76561198128704797", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "12", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1554811200.0}
