{"text": "Command and Conquer didn't invent the RTS but it was arguably one of the most influential early genre innovators, offering the chance to construct and command a modern military (with some special science fiction inspired units) in order to dominate your opponent. The following year, Westwood followed up Command and Conquer with the even better alternate history inspired Red Alert which imagines a world where a time traveling Albert Einstein prevents Hitler from coming into power leaving an unchecked Soviet Union to become the antagonizing world power during World War 2. After Electronic Arts purchased the franchise and ran it into the ground, C&C loves were left without hope that anything remotely worth playing would bare the C&C name again... Fortunately, instead of allowing the franchise die out or continue to be soiled by awful attempts to recapture the magic of past titles, EA has opted to release Command & Conquer and Red Alert bundled together with all of their expansions ready to run on modern hardware at a 4k resolution with Steam workshop support and other small tweaks.  With the tap of the spacebar in-game players can toggle between the original graphics and the updated high rez sprites. The game does and incredible job of not deviating from the original artwork leaving series veterans with crisp, clean, familiar imagery. The delightfully kitschy live action cutscenes have been enhanced a bit, presenting far better than they originally did back in the days of 640Ã—480 resolution monitors. In addition to visual enhancements, both titles allow player to create custom playlists from the extensive selection of audio tracks from both game's soundtracks. Of course steam workshop compatibility and a custom map browser also make multiplayer and skirmish maps more enjoyable once you have graduated from the official selection of maps and the map creator is pretty easy to manage if you are feeling creative. It's important to note that gameplay has not been altered. Path-finding AI in 1995 was terrible and that has not been addressed here. Expect units to not recognize obstacles and drive in circles trying to find a way forward and idle units do not automatically move to allow other units on the move to pass choke points. You will have to do a bit of micromanaging, especially on more complex custom maps. This is not an issue for me and other gamers raised on the franchise, but those accustomed to more modern RTS experiences should be aware if they have little patience for such antiquated gameplay.     Ultimately EA manages to deliver a really nice package with Command & Conquer Remastered, preserving the core of the game while making it easy to run on modern hardware and easy on the eyes. There is plenty of content here between the two campaigns, special gameplay modes and skirmishes to squeeze dozens of hours out of this package and the price seems fair given the quality of the package. Those wanting a dose of nostalgia without the headache of fiddling with trying to make 25 year old games run on their current machines should buy this immediately!", "appid": "1213210", "steamid": "profiles/76561197985114832", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "62", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1603108800.0}
