{"text": "ClearMem is a great program for clearing your RAM. If you need to clear RAM then it's well worth getting. I use it primarily for two things - running Cities: Skylines and web browsing 1. Cities: Skylines - this game uses huge amounts of memory, especially if you have all the DLCs and install loads of mods. Mine uses around 40GB of memory, 16GB in RAM and 24GB in the swapfile. This causes the game to take ages to load and then runs poorly, especially if I open another program like a web browser. In tests that I did, it took 6.5 minutes to load a city without ClearMem. By running ClearMem first, it would load in just 1.5 minutes. That's a saving of 5 minutes! Running ClearMem again then reduces the RAM used to around 8GB (or less), giving me enough RAM to run a web browser simultaneously (on my 2nd monitor). Doing this without ClearMem would make my computer unstable and sometimes even crash it. The problem with Cities: Skylines is that it loads ALL of the graphics into memory, whether you use them all or not (usually you don't). So it's quite safe to move most of them to the swapfile since they aren't being used anyway. Occasionally there's a brief pause when the game needs to load some complex new graphics, but that's not a problem. If you're serious about playing this game and don't have a ton of RAM, ClearMem is an excellent solution. The same should be true of any other games that use a huge amount of memory. 2. Web Browsing. I have a habit of opening lots of tabs when I browse the web (and I'm sure I'm not the only one), often loading many YouTube videos that I plan to watch later. In doing this the RAM usage keeps going up and up until it uses most of it, making my computer unstable and sometimes even crashing it. ClearMem prevents this from happening. I have it running all the time when I browse the web. I use the Auto RAM Clearing function to clear the RAM whenever it goes over a certain percentage (I like 30%). That stops my browser from stealing all my RAM and doesn't affect performance at all. The Web RAM Watchdog doesn't seem to work for me (maybe because I'm using Firefox?). You can set exclusions for any programs that you don't want to have cleared from RAM. NOTE: Several reviewers claim that this software is a scam or snake oil, but it's not. It does exactly what it claims to do, not what many people seem to think it should do. It doesn't improve performance, it doesn't give you more memory, it doesn't improve speed. It simply clears RAM. If you don't need to clear RAM then you don't need it, but if you do, it's extremely useful.", "appid": "780100", "steamid": "profiles/76561197998031554", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "23", "votes_funny": "3", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1603627200.0}
