{"text": "Assassin's Creed Unity serinin adÄ±nÄ±n lekelenmesinin temel sebebi denebilir sanÄ±rÄ±m. PC portu rezalet denecek kadar kÃ¶tÃ¼. Sisteminiz ne kadar iyi olursa olsun mutlaka performans sorunlarÄ± yaÅŸÄ±yorsunuz ve oyun buglarla dolu. Onun dÄ±ÅŸÄ±nda oyuna bakacak olursak Ã§ok sÄ±ÄŸ bir hikayesi var. Kesinlikle kÃ¶tÃ¼ yazÄ±lmÄ±ÅŸ bir hikayeye sahip. Senaryo adeta \"bir an Ã¶nce yazalÄ±m da bitsin\" kafasÄ±nda yazÄ±lmÄ±ÅŸ gibi. Ana karakter Arno'nun karakter geliÅŸimi Ã§ok Ã¶zensiz olmuÅŸ. Oyunun iyi yanlarÄ±na gelirsek zÄ±rh ve silah Ã§eÅŸitliliÄŸinin son derece bol olmasÄ± oyunun en gÃ¼zel yanÄ± olabilir. Karakteri dilediÄŸiniz gibi kiÅŸiselleÅŸtirebiliyorsunuz ve bu konuda mÃ¼mkÃ¼n olduÄŸunca Ã¶zgÃ¼rlÃ¼k saÄŸlanmÄ±ÅŸ oyuncuya. Assassin's Creed Unity PC'de uzak durmanÄ±z gereken bir oyun fakat konsolda yÃ¼ksek beklentiye kapÄ±lmayarak, zaman geÃ§irmek adÄ±na oynanabilecek ve keyif alÄ±nabilecek bir oyun. Unity'den nefret etmiyorum ama serinin en az sevdiÄŸim oyunu oldu.", "appid": "289650", "steamid": "profiles/76561198033203548", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "69", "votes_funny": "9", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1498564800.0}
{"text": "I beat the main game on normal difficulty, singleplayer. I purchased Party Hard before it showed up in bundles and before its Streaming integration features. I went in with no expectations. Party Hard has a simple premise that seems like it could be super enjoyable. Go to a party and attempt to kill everyone there. Looking at the screenshots and trailers makes it seem even better with the wide variety of locations and insanity shown. Thats what I'm sure many people fell for, the seeming variety presented on the store page.  The game consists of walking around a single screen populated with npcs who aimlessly wander around the stage. The default character has a one hit kill melee attack that works in a very limited area. There are also a variety of interactables in each stage that can also kill party-goers or otherwise make the task easier like items and secret passages. The challenge comes from the fact that the npcs will discover dead bodies and promptly call the authorities. A single cop will then enter the stage bagging up any bodies that have been reported and any others he may find. If the npc who discovers the crime sees you in close proximity to the body then the cop will target you and chase down your character for a limited time, if he catches you the game ends. As the game progresses other npcs will be introduced who can also take you down for various reasons.  On paper this sounds great, a stealth game with all sorts of ways to kill the targets. The issue comes from, at least in my playthrough, every level ends up playing exactly the same with little variation regardless of design. There are four types of traps you can find in a level: 1. Single kill traps that activate if you are standing right next to the trap and an npc 2. Instant activation traps that kill whoever is in the traps hitzone when activated 3. Explosives that go off after a certain amount of time, usually waiting for someone to touch them first. 4. Poisoned refreshments which kill any npc that interacts with them until its kill limit has been reached. This sounds like you have tons of options, especially when you watch the trailer and see all the quirky fun traps there are. In reality though, after one or two runs on a level you figure out what each trap does and start each stage just running to each one and activating them. There isn't really any planning involved. The npcs are truly random as far as I can tell meaning there is no way to predict them or encourage them to go to a specific area. Even killing someone to make them call the police can send them to one of two phones, sometimes the closest one, sometimes not, meaning you cant even account for that. So when you cant plan where npc are going to go you cant time traps appropriately, plus the default character is incredibly slow so most of the time if people are in range of an instant trap you wont be close enough to activate it in time to take advantage. So instead you just activate all the proximity traps+poison right away and activate the others whenever the chance arises. There are occaisonally some 'support' units you can call in to take out some people but they have a limited amount of kills before they leave similar to the poison, essentially each level has a certain amount of party goers that is guaranteed to be taken out by certain traps. The explosives are the most frustrating because an npc has to be very close to activate it, not in the blast zone but right next to the damn bomb. so even if you could kill a third of the targets with one bomb, you likely wont because no npc will actually approach the damn thing until the majority of them have dispersed.  So after activating all possible traps the game gets even more boring. Because the npcs are random you can't predict their movements, not even a little. This means you have to wait for them to be isolated which can take forever depending on the amount of npcs in an area. You can try and kill bunches of people in rapid sucession but more often than not this will lead to some npc randomly coming by to report you. None of the levels are hard. 90% of time I lost because I tried to do something other than slowly pick off targets. I lost for trying to have fun. Perhaps the greatest sign that the gameplay is flawed is that in a few levels I figured out how to exploit the cops. They seem to be autopathed to take the shortest route to your character. So with some dumb luck I actually found some spots that ,if you walk in and out of, will change the shortest route making the cop run in circles till his timer runs out. Strangely though these were the levels I could have the most fun. I could string together wacky combos and attempt things that I simply couldn't during normal gameplay. I could actually make plans that, while they didnt always work, at least let me have some creativity with the game. Thats what I think is the biggest problem with this game, freedom. In games like Hotline Miami, Deadbolt and Gunpoint you can count on your enemies reacting in certain ways (even with some variation) This allows you to plan ahead and approach the game in your own way. Party Hard's lack of any reliable elements, save for the cops, make it so there is only one way to really play it and that way isnt very fun. Its worth pointing out that I only played a couple of the DLC missions and only fiddled around with one or two of the alternate characters. I was already burnt out by the time I unlocked all that stuff to really see if anything would change. The short time I spent with the extra content was slightly more enjoyable but not enough to redeem the hours I spent on the main campaign. While it certainly isnt central, the story is garbage, I'll bet its 'big twist' was guessed by at least half the players before it happened. The story's attempt at a serious tone also doesnt match the goofiness of the game itself. The music is decent but after playing a level for the fourth or fifth time it gets really tiring (Just like real club music) Summary: +Interesting idea and premise +Quirky stages and interactions +A lot of content past the main campaign ~Music ~Art -Poorly Executed -Random -Bad/Pointless level design  -Charm wears off fast", "appid": "356570", "steamid": "profiles/76561198041006664", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "11", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1485864000.0}
