{"text": "I may be one of the people who strongly disagrees with playtonic's choice to get political with their IP, shaft pc players  with launch day release time, and have exceptionally incompetent forum moderation, but I'll keep this review exclusively about the game and not the company... because boy is there plenty wrong with the game.  I finished it in about 17 hours, but could have finished it sooner (in about 13 hours) had I gone straight to the last boss as soon as it was unlocked. Keep in mind, I was playing with a mouse and keyboard, but I'll mostly point out things that have nothing to do with my choice of gameplay equipment.  Most of the levels are enormous, and suffer from a very non-cohesive level design where big chunks of the world have a few pagies in one corner, and a large chunk has some in another. There isn't a whole lot of free roaming possibilities with a lot of the worlds because of how large they are. If you go roaming without an intended goal, you'll come across things to do, sure. But about half-way through completion of that world, any roaming you do is more likely to make you feel like you're wandering aimlessly, rather than exploring to find something to do. This is   for an exploration platformer. The level design itself has some problems though. There are places where the player can get stuck and be forced to die in order to get unstuck based on the moves they currently have available to them. Granted you really have to try, but if you're desperate looking for something, it's bound to happen. The game seriously needs a new tonic that adds a wayfinder arrow pointing to regions of the level/collectibles you have not found. It's THAT big and THAT boring to revisit places trying to find the last collectibles.  The camera is a nightmare. More-so than I think any platformer I have ever played. If it has no room to move in a direction you want, it simply won't. It won't snap to the player, it won't turn the player invisible if it's forced to get right up close next to the back of the player's head. It won't clip through solid objects and turn them invisible to try and keep providing the player with a view of what's happening, it just refuses at times, but jumps around more quickly than the player was expecting at other times. Not to mention way too many areas in the game where the camera is forced into a specific perspective that it doesn't need to be in, much like it's trying to give you a 2d-platformer camera when you wouldn't actually want one. There wasn't nearly enough work put into the camera, and the worst experience I had with it was while underwater. If you try to swim down, you would want to LOOK down to see where you're going. But with Yooka Laylee's camera, it will constantly snap back up and forward directly behind the player (which effects how the player can move) over and over again. It's a terrible nightmare of poorly-coded frustration.  If you're playing on a keyboard, they literally didn't bind \"B\" to cancel to any key, meaning players were getting stuck in challenges they could not refuse to try again on if they failed, because P is pause, and ESC is pause, so you have to double tap P and then hit ESC as a hotfix to try and select cancel.  For some reason you can collide with scenery foliage and ferns in the ground, as well as debris from breakable objects, which get you stuck for a couple seconds until they disappear. Very annoying if enemies are nearby.  This happened to me several times. If you don't clear the area of nearby enemies before talking to an npc, they are likely to run up to your occupied player characters as you talk to said npc, and as soon as you stop talking, you will take unavoidable damage. Even Banjo Kazooie had it so nearby enemies automatically and instantaneously de-agro'd on you when you lost control of your character. How was this overlooked!?  The pink butterflies act as both health pickups and energy pickups, but not in one. Eating a butterfly gives health, touching them like a collectible gives energy, but not vice versa. In races, this is exceptionally annoying because it's hard to gauge where the butterfly is that you have to touch while in motion. They also don't cast shadows AND float around unpredictably, so it's way more difficult than it ever should be.  Player can take unavoidable damage from certain unskippable cutscenes if the cutscene ends at just the wrong time, especially with world 1 boss.  Mostly with world 2 transformation. You can't move backwards, and it's a   transformation. You also cannot move left or right without moving forward, and are required to do precise platforming as this transformation. Unfair and nightmare-inducing. The 'tarnsform back' feature for this transformation is also broken, can be interrupted and result in a spastic seizure pulsation of the character if you hold shift and then attack.  Lizard Lash is the ability Yooka starts out with that is used to grab on to things with his tongue, such as butterflies or powerups. It can be done while jumping, but not while doing the bat flutter move, which you will feel as though should be easily possible, when it's not. Later moves that upgrade Lizard Lash are TERRIBLY inconsistent, mostly in world 3 where the functionality of the move is just ALL over the place and results in unfair damage/death.  Some are fun and straight forward, others are horrendously broken, unfair, pointlessly frustrating, and make you despise Rextro more than any other character. World 1 arcade game is more frustrating than fun, as is world 4 and 5 arcade games, but world 4 \"Capital Cashino\" especially. The controls are literally broken. It's called Hurdle Hijinx, you run straight forward and dodge obstacles by changing lanes. If you change lanes too fast, the game gets confused and LOCKS YOUR ABILITY TO CHANGE LANES, guaranteeing death, and making the second pagie for a high score next to impossible without surgical precision and 15 tries later.  Certain challenges such as world 4 transformation escort missions don't have their target rings removed if you fail and then refuse the challenge, meaning the ring stays there for the rest of the tim you're in the world, but does nothing, confusing new players into thinking it activates something when it doesn't. There are many oversights like this where the devs just didn't pay close enough attention to how they coded it.  The Hunter tonic makes lone collectibles whistle periodically when you are near them to help you find them, but ONLY if you've missed them beforehand, and left the area, which the tonic doesn't specify.  Some characters/enemies sound thematic for what they are, others are just a guy in his 30s making monster sounds as though he's entertaining children, and it sounds obnoxious and ridiculous, instead of stylistic.  Certain tunes sound like they are from a poorly-produced 80s children cartoon, while others sound on par with the rest of the soundtrack. It's very off-putting.  Overall, it's not worth 40 dollars, even if you LOVE Banjo-Kazooie. Wait for it to be 25 or less on sale, or don't bother. I adore Banjo-Kazooie, but have to give this a 6/10 and not recommend it for $40 in its current state. Too many incompetent design-choices that come at the expense of the player.", "appid": "360830", "steamid": "profiles/76561197979947064", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "62", "votes_funny": "2", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1492084800.0}
