{"text": "62 gigabytes of trash. This game is a let down in every sense and it has no sense of direction. TL;DR: This game has an identity crisis. It WANTS to be realistic, but the style of game prevents it from being fun if that is the case. It suffers from bad balance, unrealistic aspects despite its advertising, and unfriendly hardware and software requirements for a \"wide-appeal\" game. Onto the review: Every Tom Clancy game I've ever played has had a realistic, modern war-time setting. The Rainbow Six series, especially, has given me the sense that this series is specifically about realism, and not fantastic shooting. With this in mind, Rainbow Six siege succeeded on launch. It was a realistic shooter, but with a multiplayer aspect. I didn't play it on launch, but judging by the older operators, the remnants of that first version are clear. But here lies the problem. Rainbow Six Siege isn't a realistic first-person shooter against AI enemies. It's a relatively fast paced (relative to older Tom Clancy's games) 5v5 competitive multiplayer shooter. It has elements comparable to games such as Counter-Strike and League of Legends.  So why is that bad? Well it's simple. Realism and Competitive viability are two distinct, incompatible things. Having a realistic-firing gun means you can't have reliable spray patterns, predictable recoil, and in some cases, a fun time. Having realistic sound is impressive, and I definitely commend the team for applying such fantastic sound design... But it â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ sucks for multiplayer. It's horrible. Hearing sounds from the opposite direction, although realistic, is bad for competitive play because that's just not how games work. It's not how things work in Counter-Strike.  However, this game still insists on being the most realistic competitive shooter. I don't play the game anymore, so I'm fine with that, but what I'm not fine with is this game lacking realism in its most recent operator releases. Let's take a few examples, but I haven't played every operator and I definitely haven't seen footage of them all, or properly understand their gadgets. First, let's start with Mira. Bad pun name aside, her gadget is... well, a mirror. It's a one-way mirror that allows you to create new angles that give a distinct defenders advantage, while simultaneously giving away the position of the defender. It's a cool, balanced gadget idea that I think makes this kind of game good... But it makes no sense. One-way mirrors work by having a dark room on one side, allowing the glass to create a reflective surface, instead of a translucent one.  I've never seen a Mira place a mirror in a dark room looking into a bright one, but it still works just fine. I, personally, have no problem with this. It's unrealistic, but the concept behind it is completely balanced, and fun, and is a very new concept to games, outside of destroying terrain. But it's NOT realistic, and this game is all about realism.  In fact, most new operators, and most new updates seem to remove the realistic aspects. The game is clearly shifting, at least in its new stages, towards competitive viability... So why aren't all realistic aspects gone?  This moves onto my next point, the important point. The game is removing realistic aspects slowly and pushing towards more balance and more competitive options, in place of \"realistic\" things. But there are so many unrealistic AND uncompetitive things in this game that it's just... strange. Why do 9mm pistols one-shot headshot at a distance of two hundred metres against people who wear large, padded helmet. That's not realistic, and high fire-rate submachine guns spraying into a room is more likely to get a lucky headshot in this kind of game than DMRs or low fire-rate assault rifles.  And let's talk about hitboxes. This game has horrible hitboxes. Hitboxes should be the same for every character, regardless of their size, and their appearance should be modelled around those hitboxes, not the other way round. It's simple game-creation and they've completely failed on this point. The joke about Ash's head hitbox is a popular one in the community, but it certainly stems from a real issue.  And finally, I mentioned creating new angles as a cool game mechanic. It is a cool one, but the idea behind Mira's mirror also gives away the position of the defender. However, you can create tiny holes in any wall, watching any angle, where you can shoot a single bullet with an ACOG on an SMG (How is that loadout balanced?) and get a single headshot. The expected counter play is \"You should know these wall-break positions, and should be able to prefire them, or counter-play them with operators like Blackbeard or a shield-bearing operator\". Cool, but also you can place those holes anywhere, any time, and can choose to. It's a really, really bad idea, and creates an issue similar to one League of Legends has: You can lose a game in the picking stage.  League of Legends, especially in lower ELOs, has a very common issue where you can lose a game simply from the drafting stage, the stage before a game where you pick and ban champions. This issue usually doesn't happen as players gain more familiarity with different roles, and learn new champions, but in lower ELOs where players only know a single champion and a single role, if everyone follows this motive, eventually you're going to run into a problem. And quite frequently, you do, having team compositions with no tanks, or fully AD or AP are quite common, and can literally cause you to lose the game, just from bad composition.  Now what's the comparison in Siege? Well, it's not as prevalent as in League, but it's certainly still there. Not having a shield operator gives you five operators, all with proper weapons, all watching angles, but also prevents you from pushing locations that have small hole breaks that you don't know about, or certain Mirror positions. There's a trade-off, but it's very clear that shield operators are a better choice for an organised team.  There are also a few minor things that can't go without mention: This game is supposed to be competitively viable. Why is it 62 gigabytes and barely runs on a GTX 1060 on some of the newer maps? Again, identity issue here. They want realistic, rainy maps in southern UK, but that â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ barely runs on 2016 hardware, and considering when this game was released, and its game style, \"you just need to upgrade\" is NOT an excuse. As well, most other maps run fine, so it's clearly not an issue for the developers to optimise maps. This is only an issue because you can't select the maps you play on. As well, the ranking system is... scuffed. It's far too fluid, the complete opposite of CS:GO's. When playing this game's ranked mode, I EXPECTED myself to rank up or down based on a win or loss, because ranks are generally separated by 100 MMR difference, and from my experience, wins awarded roughly 90 MMR points, and loses deducted roughly 70. CS:GO suffers from the opposite issue, but at least you can't lose your entire division from a few bad games. My recommendation for the game devs is to spend less time making fancy graphics, and more time balancing the game. My recommendation for players is to find another game to play. If you want realistic first-person shooter games, literally any of the other Tom Clancy's games will suffice. If you want a competitively viable, fairly balanced game, I could recommend a plethora of games, but in terms of first-person shooters, CS:GO is a good contender.", "appid": "359550", "steamid": "profiles/76561198087883181", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "4", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1555070400.0}
{"text": "I can put my finger on it, it just feels sterile, a vast empty nothingness, controls are awkward, landing is a pain, the jumpdrive feels weird, kind of takes away from the immersion, I played it with max settings and felt a bit underwhelmed visually. Its a shame really because Ive had this game on my wish list for a long time and was eager to try it but having come from playing no mans sky with all its faults i can say the game play is more fluid then elite dangerous, although comparing them is a bit unfair as elite clearly gears towards simulation style space flying and no mans sky is totally arcady in that sense. I think unless you are into games like X3 you would find it dificult to pick this up and have any amount of fun with it, making money is a total grind and shuttling between stations becomes a shore, and bear in mind a played 109 minutes, became repetitive really quick. Overall 6\\10 for me.", "appid": "359320", "steamid": "profiles/76561197973647025", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1511524800.0}
