{"text": "So I spent probably 8 hours playing with a friend today (the 2nd or 3rd day I've owned the game) since we were both off of work and I gotta say I have mixed emotions about this game. It was hyped up to be amazing and I don't see what all the hype is about.  First of all, unless you play on the fastest speed setting, it is PAINFULLY slow and boring. It's even kinda boring with the speed all the way up.  You don't really have any control over battles whatsoever, your production of certain things inexplicably dips down into the negative for no apparent reason all of the time, there's never enough energy / minerals to do anything, the research available seems completely random, which means you can easily get screwed, and on top of all of that, by the later part of the game some race from outside of the galaxy came in and started dominating everyone. I thought I was pretty secure with a fleet at around 30k power and this race of creatures had multiple fleets at ~60k... there's no possible way to defend against that.  For most of the time you're just sitting there all bored waiting for things to be built and for time to pass. The graphics are 'meh' at best, the music is 'meh' at best (and very repetitive as this game is usually played for long periods of time), and there's a lot of gameplay mechanics that either don't make sense or are hidden away and even with the full tutorial on, you never get an explanation as to how and why many things work they way they do.  I'm super glad I got this in the Humblebundle monthly deal because if I had spent full price on this I would be asking for a refund in a heartbeat. It's not 'bad' per se - I just don't get the appeal. Who wants to sit for hours and hours slowly building up a civilization, just to get r@ped by impossibly strong invaders near the end? Game last forever, even on the smallest map size, and generally speaking the entire experience is a bore. I am sure that for people who actually enjoy this type of game, it's great... but holy cow is this a tedious and boring experience for me... and this is coming from someone who actually likes many types of games that most people consider boring. If you are thinking about buying this game and you have no experience whatsoever with this type of game, let me break it down for you in a nutshell:  For the first SEVERAL hours you will be learning how to play the game as it is very complex, and even when the tutorial hints are over there are many things that are not made clear, things don't make sense at all sometimes. The gameplay is painfully slow and combat comes down to having the larger fleet / superior technology. There's no skill involved in terms of the battles... it's just a pure numbers game. I think that if you're a fan of really LONG games like Risk and want to play this against friends with no AI or fallen empires, you'd probably like it, but personally I feel like I just wasted 18 hours of my life in the hopes that the game would eventually get good. It didn't.", "appid": "281990", "steamid": "profiles/76561198029579963", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1494936000.0}
{"text": "Sea of Thieves can be a blast with friends, but you will likely find yourself getting bored with trying to complete the more challenging things in the game, due to the only reward being cosmetics for your character/ship. This game is really what you make it, and it is very hard to â€œmakeâ€ fun without playing with a group of friends. Ultimately, I would not recommend people to buy Sea of Thieves unless you know you will have a group of friends that will commit to playing with you. Otherwise this game may just end up another game of the day within your friend group.  \tSea of Thieves is an open world, multiplayer focused, pirate game by Rare. The game recently rereleased for steam; I played the game when it originally released alongside the PC version of the Xbox game pass, so this gives me a chance to see if the game has evolved in any major ways since I last played. It is fantastic to see â€œMicrosoft Studioâ€ games releasing outside the Microsoft store, even if it does seem to be much later than anyone would like. \tMultiplayer seems to be the focus and draw for a game like Sea of Thieves. The world seems empty and hollow without seeing other players, friendly or otherwise, this discouraged solo play for me. It is sad to see a game like this be hindered by the multiplayer focus; This does just seem to be the byproduct of the games industry constantly pushing out unfinished games with the lure of â€œour players are the gameâ€. I had a ton of fun while playing with friends, collecting loot from islands, playing sea shanties, fighting a kraken, or just sailing on the open ocean. Sadly, none of this really felt the same while playing by myself. \tVisually, Sea of Thieves was surprising. The cartoonish aesthetic fits perfectly and I really couldnâ€™t imagine this game without it. The character designs can seem a bit unpolished, but I think this just leans into the rough aspect of living on the open seas. The water physics are phenomenal and work as you would expect them to, no matter what you try. Sailing waves, swimming into a storm, or collecting floating loot, the water physics just work.   \tThe major reason I couldnâ€™t find myself getting engrossed is the lack of meaningful player progression. The main thing to work towards is cosmetic items and getting more missions to grind. There are a metric ton of cosmetic items to earn and while that is nice, the only difference from someone who has played the game for 1000 hours and someone like me with 20ishâ€¦ is visuals. With cosmetics being the only player progression, you may expect there to be no in-game micro transactions, but sadly there areâ€¦ more cosmetics.  -HiPFiRED", "appid": "1172620", "steamid": "profiles/76561198070412659", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "319", "votes_funny": "16", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1594641600.0}
