{"text": "I really wanted to like this game because I like the pacing and epic feel of an expansive JRPG. I also read reviews describing this game as darker and more mature, making me think the character relationships/dialogue/etc. would be at that next level above tropy anime garbage. Nope. Stupid fanservice costumes, rigid dialogue, characters that appear out of nowhere and behave/interact in ways that make no sense unless you think about the meta of \"what does the plot dictate that it needs to move forward?\" Basic, overwrought anime tropes abound, and the world building is atrocious. The combat seems like it could be really interesting if the depth provided was at all necessary; it turns out button mashing is fine. The maps are simplistic and don't feel lived-in--just a couple platforms with a bridge or branching path here and there. I wouldn't even mind the little fashion aspect of the game if it had anything to do with the rest of the game. It breaks any little bit of immersion when you are supposed to be trying to be inconspicuous and you're wearing an insane outfit, or worse yet, being spotted because you are wearing a black cape when you have Velvet dressed completely casually. Maybe the characters would be more fun to look at if they actually moved a little bit during in-game cutscenes and didn't just stand like freaky robots waiting their turn to give a line of dialogue. If you're younger, are an anime nerd, and are looking for a more casual--but long--RPG, then this might be a good game for you. It's definitely not for me. Just because there is death and ambiguous morality in a game does not make it deep or dark or mature.", "appid": "429660", "steamid": "profiles/76561197964483541", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "6", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1524398400.0}
