{"text": "Pathfinder: Kingmaker is a CRPG featuring kingdom management.  The kingdom management is a chore, very little of what you choose to do is reflected in the areas you can visit or even on the overland map. All your villages and towns you build look exactly the same bar three (one of which is your capital.) You assign people to tasks and then cross your fingers. If the die roll goes badly then your kingdom can fall apart very easily and if -5 loyalty sends the populace into panic, +5 loyalty on the next card won't be anywhere close to bringing things back to the level. You're a ruler and you have a military, but you can't make them do anything. Monsters in the woods? The Baron will sort it! Neighbouring kingdom sending raiding parties across the border? Yep, the Baron will sort it! Some random bloke didn't find his way home? Call the Baron! I know this stuff is the meat of most CRPGs but if you give me some degree of power, please at least also give me a chance to use it. It's incredibly frustrating how little any of the kingdom stuff actually matters, but you have to engage with it because if your kingdom fails it's a game over. As for the actual, party-based role playing side of things... Meh. It looks lovely and there is fun to be had but it just seems to drag on and on and nothing is ever really interesting. You start out weak and you level and, well... half the time, it's 4 HP and that's about it. I know this is from the table top rules but 4 HP can feel like a real lifeline when you're playing table top - you know where it all goes, you know how close you were to death that one time, those 4 points can be enough to keep you active just one more round. Here, because it's RTwP rather than turn-based, it feels hard to keep track of anything and nothing really seems interesting. You buff your party, you send them to fight and then... well, things just start happening all over the place. Yes you can slow things down and also set triggers to auto pause but then the pacing is all off, it's no fun and honestly an actual turn based mode giving you time to think about things would work so much better. I'm no stranger to cheesing a RTwP game (I remember pulling Gnolls or Hobgoblins a few at a time through the mine in Baldur's Gate, then just napping for 8 hours whilst all the other baddies just ignored you) and you can do the same here, but you need supplies so it's just another thing to have to consider that doesn't really add anything to the game. Travel on the map is slow and boring and you just have to rest all the bloody time. Random encounters are dull and if it ever says there's someone friendly, well, it's basically one specific NPC who you will encounter over and over again because you keep accepting the encounter just in case it's someone new. The areas themselves are really pretty but maps get reused and a lot of the time there really isn't anything interesting or unique to find. Less areas with more interesting stuff to see, do and interact with would really have gone a long way in my opinion. It also doesn't help that new and potentially very important NPCs or events can spawn in areas you've already visited with no indication that they're there. So even if you've fully cleared that tiny riverbank map, make sure to revisit it time and again because otherwise you may find your fledgling kingdom short staffed for a long while. Overall I just can't recommend the game and I think the achievement percentages speak for themselves in some ways. apparently, only 6.4% of Steam players have actually beaten the game. For now, I won't be one of them. Maybe I'll come back in a few months and finish things off but right now, I just cannot be bothered.", "appid": "640820", "steamid": "profiles/76561197994149540", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "3", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1571054400.0}
{"text": "Historically inaccurate, since when did they have red dots and holo sights in WW2? Soldiers are tired of a sprint after what 10 seconds? I believe back in WW2 soldiers were fit human beings and sprint for longer that 10 seconds. Even an out of shaped guy would be able to out run a soldier at this point. Maps look pretty but are way to small.. which causes the bad spawnings and just being spawnkilled. Only fun game mode is the War mode the rest is just crap running and gunning (well run for 10 seconds that is). Game is badly optimized, resulting in stuttering, and random drops especially with particals.  Aiming feels off, like it's being dragged through mud and then suddenly slips over ice, causing under and over aim. Movement feels sluggish like I don't have full controll over the movement of my character. They don't use dedicated servers which leads to no server browser. WWII is using peer-to-peer connection in 2017.. causing bad hit registration and giving the host an advantage. I was hoping CoD would be good again, as the last CoD I played was BO2, but they missed their target by miles.. They should really look at what made CoD2 and MW so great and go from there. I feel like they lost their touch and overthinking instead of listening to the fanbase.  Thanks for the Beta tho. Even though it made me decide not to get this game. Edit: Second day I'm playing just to see if my judgement was fair. And what did I come across a bunch of aimbotters. Please do not pre-order/buy with this bad of an anti-cheat.  Instead save yourself the $60+ and buy you grandma, mom, or wife some flowers, you will get more out of it than this failure of a game.", "appid": "696790", "steamid": "profiles/76561198029253585", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "2", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1506686400.0}
